John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective endeavours.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for further higher education, their chosen career and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of developing and adopting a personalised school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular subject and in demand within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his native language, the message will reach his heart".
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build trusting relationships with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's examinations, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of pupils who studied foreign languages scored highest.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students scored highest with praise in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish scored highest.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as a key skill for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages as a subject choice are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons employees gave for the difficulty in filling jobs were 17% attributable to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were not able to speak a foreign language at a level sufficient to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language learning is so important for children today.
Knowledge of more languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking at 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in independent schools with specialised teaching staff.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future.
It cannot be denied that at this moment, in a global trading system, languages remain fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It's got to be done right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
