"We do not see any satisfactory response from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no security in our national security, and in these circumstances we absolutely refuse to unilaterally disarm first".
Although Ri reiterated the well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a phased denuclearization that would be rewarded to North Korea on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever meeting between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal agreement to end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls for loosening the tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need for 'denuclearization first' and to increase the pressure level with sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive way and even opposes the 'declaration of end of war', Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust".
Ri did not refer to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader had announced at the UN earlier this week.
The minister pointed to the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months and added: "If the counterpart to this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the US, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be at this point".
But even so, the tone of Ri's speech was markedly different from last year's speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said that it was inevitable to target US territory with North Korean missiles after the evil president Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely" destroy North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in embarking on the path of disarmament, but said much more still needs to be done and that sanctions would remain in place until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday Trump said he had no deadline, saying that "whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
