A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all its students to get more sleep in an attempt to counter the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights fueled by caffeine.
One university scholar found that students at the world's top university often have no idea of the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
Finally, a girl came to me and said, "Why am I only being told this now, when I'm a senior?"
She said that no one had ever told her anything about the "importance of sleep", which surprised me very much, she told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being taught for the first time this year, explains the essential concepts of how good sleep habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is a picture of a dormitory room, where students can select coffee cups, curtains, gym shoes and books so they can learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are told how lack of sleep in the long term can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of the choice to smoke cigarettes", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of "pride" linked to "sleeping at night" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Getting enough and good quality sleep should be the students' secret weapon to fight stress, exhaustion, anxiety, he explained, and should even help prevent weight gain as lack of sleep puts the brain in a sluggish mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student enrolled in the chemistry and physics biology department, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for the whole campus.
