Imagine for a moment, you stayed up all night watching the famous Bellator 206 only to be denied a view of the main event.
The program from San Jose included 13 fights, including six on the main card, and was to be broadcast in the UK overnight, live on Channel 5.
At 6am, just as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were preparing to clash, viewers in the UK were stunned when Peppa Pig appeared on screen.
Some have been left low after staying up until the early hours of the morning specifically for combat.
On Twitter, one fan described the move to children's cartoons as "a kind of bad joke".
"The government's policy is that at 6 a.m. that content is no longer appropriate, so we had to switch to children's programming", said Dave Schwartz, Bellator's senior vice president for marketing and communications, when asked about the show.
"Pig's feathers", yeah.
 Bellator chairman Scott Coker said they would work on programming to include UK viewers in the future.
"I think when I think about replay, I think we can probably find a solution", Coker said.
But it's six o'clock on Sunday morning and we won't be able to find a solution until Sunday in our time zone, Monday in theirs.
But we're working on it.
Believe me, when the schedule changed, there were a lot of messages coming in and no one was friendly.
We were trying to solve the problem, we thought it was a technical problem.
But it wasn't. It was a government issue.
I promise you, next time it won't happen.
We're going to limit it to five fights instead of six -- as we normally do -- and we've been trying to get as much for the fans, and we just talked about it.
This is an unfortunate situation.
Tom Daley felt inferior because of his sexuality
Olympic swimmer Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior because of his sexuality - but this gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn't realize until he got to high school that "not everyone is like me".
Speaking on the first episode of Radio 4's Desert Island Discs, hosted by Lauren Laverne, he said he had made his voice heard about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also stated that becoming a parent made him less concerned about winning the Olympics.
The longtime host of the program, Kirsty Young, took a series of months off due to illness.
Introducing himself as an outcast in Laverne's first show, Daley stated that he felt "less than anyone else" as he grew up because "it wasn't socially acceptable that he liked both boys and girls".
He said, "Today, the feeling of being less than, and feeling different, were the things that really gave me the strength and the energy to be successful".
He wanted to prove he was something, he said, so as not to disappoint anyone if they discovered his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist has become a high-profile LGBT activist and used his face at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal to more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he made his voice heard because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to give "hope" to others.
The three-time world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man - the American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 - caught him by surprise.
Daley married the Oscar winner, who's 20 years his senior, last year, but he said the age difference was never a problem.
"When you go through so much at a young age - he went to his first Olympics when he was 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was hard to find someone his age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The two became parents in June, of a baby boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "entire perspective" has changed.
"If you had asked me last year, it was all about the fact that I was going to win a gold medal", he said.
You know, there are things more important than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medalist is Robbie.
His son is named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father had not accepted the fact that he was dying and that one of the last things he asked was if they had tickets for London 2012 already - because he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him you're not going to be around so you can be in the front row, Dad", he said.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and until he actually stopped and died, I hadn't realized he wasn't invincible yet", he said.
The following year Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics, winning bronze.
"I just knew it was what I had dreamed of all my life - swimming in front of a home crowd at the Olympics, there was no better feeling", he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song - Proud by Heather Small - which had a special meaning for him in the build-up to the Olympics and still makes him feel bad.
Desert Island Discs is on BBC Radio 4 on Sundays at 11:15 BST.
Out-of-shape Mickelson was benched in the Ryder Cup on Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson will set a record on Sunday when he plays his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he'll have to get back in shape to avoid becoming an unfortunate milestone.
Mickelson, playing in the biennial event for a record 12th time, was benched by captain Jim Furyk for the fourballs and foursomes on Saturday.
Instead of being the center of the action, as he often has been for the United States, the five-time champion spent the day between cheerleading and working on his game in the ring, hoping to correct what was bothering him.
Having never been the strongest driver even at the peak of his career, the 48-year-old is not the ideal choice for the difficult Le Golf National, where the unconnected course regularly punishes misses.
And if the path itself wasn't daunting enough, Mickelson, in Sunday's ninth match, faces the defending British Open champion Francesco Molinari, who has teamed up with rookie Tommy Fleetwood to win all four of their matches this week.
If the Americans, four points down at the start of their 12 singles matches, start with a hot start, Mickelson's match could prove to be absolutely crucial.
Furyk expressed confidence in his man, not that he could say much else.
"He fully understood his role today, he slapped me on the shoulder, put his arm around me and said he would be ready for tomorrow", Furyk said.
He's got a lot of confidence.
He's a Hall of Famer and he's added so much to the teams in the past, and this week.
I probably didn't imagine playing two games.
I had imagined more, but this is the way it went and this is the way we thought it should go.
He wants to participate, just like everyone else.
Mickelson on Sunday will surpass Nick Faldo's record for most games played in the Ryder Cup.
It could mark the end of a Ryder Cup career that never even remotely mirrored the heights of his personal best.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven ties, though Furyk said his presence has brought intangible benefits to the team.
"He's funny, sarcastic, witty, likes to make fun of people, and he's a great guy to have in the boardroom", he explained.
I also think the younger players have had fun trying out against him this week, which was fun to watch.
He did more than play.
The captain of Europe, Thomas Bjorn, knows that a good advantage can quickly fade away
Thomas Bjorn, the European captain, knows from experience that a considerable advantage in the individual events of the final day of the Ryder Cup can easily turn into an uncomfortable race.
The Danish made his debut in the 1997 match in Valderrama, where the team, captained by Seve Ballesteros, despite a five-point lead from the Americans, reached the finish line with a minimal advantage, winning 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"I keep telling myself that we had a good lead in Valderrama, we had it in Brookline, where we lost, and in Valderrama where we won, but only by a small margin", said Bjorn (pictured) after watching the 2018 class win, Friday 5 to 3 and yesterday 10 to 6, at Le Golf National.
So history will prove to me and my team that it's not over.
Tomorrow we have to do our best.
You gotta go out there and do it right.
It's not over until the dots are marked on the board.
Our goal is to try and win the trophy, and that's what we have to focus on.
I always focus on the 12 players on my team, but I know who's on the other side: the best golfers in the world.
Happy with the way his family competed on that difficult golf course, Bjorn added: "I could never have gotten better.
Tomorrow is a different challenge.
Tomorrow is the individual performances, which is something else.
It's nice to be there with a teammate when things are going well, but when you're alone your golfing skills are put to the test.
That's the message we need to get to the players: tomorrow, you have to bring out the best in yourself.
Then you forget about your partner because he has to go there and bring out the best in himself.
Unlike Bjorn, his counterpart Jim Furyk will be looking for the best individual performance rather than team performance, with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas who scored three points out of four.
Furyk himself found himself on both sides of those big matches on the last day, having been part of the winning team in Brookline before losing to the European "Miracle of Medinah".
"I remember every single word", he said in response to a question about how Ben Crenshaw, captain in 1999, led his players on the final day.
Tomorrow we have 12 big games, but we want to start right away with the right foot like we did in Brookline and Medina.
When the game starts to take a certain turn, the pressure increases in the intermediate games.
So let's organize our training accordingly and classify the kids in the way we see fit, because tomorrow we're going to try to do magic.
Thomas was given the task of leading the counter-attack and facing Rory McIlroy in the top match with, in order, the other Europeans, Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, in the first half.
"I chose this order because I think it covers the journey to the end", said Bjorn about his selection for the individual matches.
Germany's new warship has been postponed again
According to local media, the latest German Navy frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era military ships, but will not be until at least next year due to faulty systems and a spike in costs.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but troubling issues following delivery have plagued the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the older Bremen-class ships.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared, and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, as it should be possible to deploy new frigates up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continuing delays mean that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its power overseas, will become obsolete by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The ill-fated Type F-125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media noted a number of crucial software and hardware flaws that rendered the ship useless if used on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly significant as the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, barely half the staff of the older Bremen class ships.
In addition, it was found that the ship was significantly overweight, which reduced its performance and limited the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
Apart from defective hardware, the cost of the whole project (including crew training) is also becoming an important issue.
It appears to have reached 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of new frigates are becoming particularly important in the light of recent alarms about the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, Parliamentary Commissioner for the Armed Forces, admitted that the navy actually lacks vessels capable of being used.
The official stated that the matter has worsened considerably over time, as the old unarmed ships have not been replaced by new ones.
His regret is that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class have been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
New research at a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use their eyesight to obtain food.
It is hoped that the findings can shed light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals in existence and guide future conservation efforts.
The study by National Trust for Scotland scientists will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as brown earrings and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Analysis of the recorded sounds by an expert will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and the way each species behaves.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed scale picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands, and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined dramatically over the past century.
Bat species are at risk from construction and development work affecting the three species and destroying their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can mosquito-killing paper and certain chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to spot insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The National Traffic Safety Service, which manages over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the three-poles and sometimes perform rescues.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first bat-only reserve at Threave Farm in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says the property is the ideal territory.
"We have a large bat area here in Threave", he said.
We have the old buildings, lots of old trees and good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats that we don't know yet, so the work we're doing here and at other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs.
It stresses the importance of bat control before maintenance on property, as the accidental destruction of a single maternal bat may kill up to 400 females and young, possibly wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their prey.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish director of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said: 'We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we don't know how their populations are doing.
Ronaldo rejects rape charges as lawyers sue German weekly
Cristiano Ronaldo has labeled the rape allegations against him as "fake news", saying people "want to get publicity" with his name.
His lawyers are preparing to sue the German weekly Der Spiegel which published the charges.
The Portuguese Juventus striker was accused of raping an American woman named Kathryn Mayorga at a Las Vegas hotel in 2009.
Der Spiegel also reported on Friday the alleged payment of $375,000 to keep quiet about what happened.
In a video on Instagram directed to his 142 million followers, in the hours following the allegations, Ronaldo, 33, dismissed the statements as "fake news".
No, no, no, no, no. I'm not going to do this.
What they said today is false, says the five-time Ballon d'Or face to the camera.
They want to advertise themselves through my name.
It's all right.
They want to be famous by using my name, but that's part of the game.
I'm happy and everything is fine", the footballer added with a smile.
According to Reuters, Ronaldo's lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel over the allegations, which they call "an inadmissible reporting of suspicions in the private sphere".
Lawyer Christian Schertz said the player will seek compensation for moral damages in proportion to the seriousness of the breach of privacy, which is probably one of the most serious personal rights violations in recent years.
The incident is alleged to have taken place in June 2009 in a suite at the Palms Casino Resort in Las Vegas.
After meeting at a nightclub, Ronaldo and Mayorga reportedly entered the soccer player's room, where he subjected her to anal violence, according to statements filed in Clark County District Court in Nevada.
Mayorga claims Ronaldo would have knelt after the incident saying he was 99 percent a "good guy" disappointed by the 1%.
The documents show that Ronaldo confirmed that the two had sexual intercourse, but that it was consensual.
Mayorga also claims that she went to the police and to the hospital, where her injuries were photographed, but later agreed to a reconciliation agreement because she felt "terrified by the retaliation" and worried about the prospect of "being publicly humiliated".
The 34-year-old is now trying to overturn the agreement, claiming she is still traumatized by the alleged incident.
Ronaldo was on the verge of joining Real Madrid from Manchester United at the time of the incident, and this summer he will join Juventus of Italy with a €100 million contract.
Brexit: UK will forever regret the loss of car manufacturers
The UK 'could forever regret' losing its status as the world's leading carmaker following Brexit, said Industry Minister Greg Clark.
He also said he was 'concerned' about Toyota UK's statements to the BBC about Britain's possible exit from the EU without a deal and the resulting temporary shutdown of production at its Burnaston plant near Derby.
"We need a deal", said Secretary Clark.
The Japanese carmaker argues that delays at the borders, in the event of a no-deal Brexit, could affect jobs.
The Burnaston plant, where Toyota Auris and Avensis are built, produced some 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
"I think if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our factory will stop", said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's general manager in Burnaston.
Concerns are growing among other British carmakers about leaving the EU without an agreement on how crossborder trade works, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, claims that after Brexit it will close its Mini plant in Oxford for a month.
The main concern is the supply chain risks faced by manufacturers in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is run on the basis of the just in time concept, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from British and European suppliers for cars on order.
If the UK leaves the EU on 29 March without a deal, there could be border disruption causing delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to keep more than one day's worth of inventory at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, so production would be halted.
Minister Clark argues that Theresa May's plan for future relations with the EU is "thought through with precision to avoid these border discomforts".
"We need a deal. We want the best deal that will allow us to not only enjoy the current success but to seize this opportunity", he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
The proof, not only from Toyota but also from other car manufacturers, is that we absolutely must be able to continue what has been a very successful supply chain.
Toyota was unable to say how long production might stop but warns that, in the long run, additional costs could reduce plant competitiveness and potentially jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked at Burnaston for 24 years and is the head of the plant's union delegates, says that workers are very concerned: 'In my experience, once jobs are cut, they are not reinstated'.
A government spokesman said: 'We have put forward a clear and credible plan for future relations with the EU'.
Trump's meeting with Rosenstein may be postponed again, the White House says.
Donald Trump's high-risk meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be "postponed" by a week, as the dispute over Judge Brett Kavanaugh continues, the White House said Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of special counsel Robert Mueller who investigates Russian interference in the election, ties between Trump advisers and Russia, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
The possibility that Trump might fire the deputy attorney general, thus jeopardizing Mueller's independence, fueled months of gossip in Washington.
Later that month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein was talking about wearing a bug to record conversations with Trump and trying to remove the president through the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied the news.
But last Monday, he went to the White House and there was a rumor that he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was at the United Nations in New York at the time, was announced for Wednesday.
Trump said he'd rather not fire Rosenstein, but then the meeting was postponed to avoid overlapping with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing where Kavanaugh and one of the women who accused him of sexual assault, Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, both testified.
On Friday, Trump ordered a week of FBI investigative questioning against Kavanaugh, further delaying the Senate's final vote.
On Sunday, Trump's spokeswoman, Sarah Sanders, appeared on Fox News.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: "No date has been set, it could be this week, I guess it will be postponed for another week considering everything that's going on with the Supreme Court.
But we'll see, and I'll keep the press updated.
Some journalists might dispute this statement: Sanders hasn't held a press briefing at the White House since September 10.
The host Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders said the lack of briefings was not due to an aversion to television journalists showing up, although he said: "I don't disagree with them showing up".
He suggested that direct contact between Trump and the press might be more frequent.
"The president has more Q&A sessions than any president before him", he said, adding without citing evidence: "We checked the numbers".
There will still be briefings, Sanders said, but if the press has the opportunity to ask the President of the United States directly, it's much better than talking to me.
We're trying to do it, like we've been doing for the last few weeks, and this will replace the press briefings and you can talk to the President of the United States.
Trump regularly answers questions when he leaves the White House or attends open sessions or press conferences with visiting dignitaries.
Press conferences are rare.
This week in New York the President may have demonstrated the reason for this by making a free-wheeling, yet bizarre, speech to a group of journalists.
The Minister of Health writes to European workers at the Scottish NHS to express his concerns about Brexit
The Minister for Health has written to EU staff working at Scotland's NHS to express the country's gratitude and wish them well to stay after Brexit.
Scottish MP Jeane Freeman sent a letter less than six months before the UK's exit from the EU.
The Scottish Government has already committed to cover the costs of applying for settled status for EU citizens working in the decentralised public services.
In his letter, Minister Freeman writes: "Throughout the summer there have been continuous negotiations between the UK and the EU on Brexit, which will lead to decisions in the autumn.
But the British Government has also prepared for a no-deal scenario.
I know this is a time of great concern for all of you.
I therefore wanted to reiterate today my appreciation for the contribution made by all staff members, irrespective of their nationality.
Colleagues from across the EU and beyond bring valuable experience and expertise that strengthens and improves the work of health services, benefiting patients and the communities we serve.
