Christion Abercrombie has undergone emergency surgery following a head injury.
Tennessee State Tigers quarterback Christion Abercrombie has undergone emergency surgery after suffering a head injury in Saturday's 31-27 loss to the Vanderbilt Commodores, reported Mike Organ of The Tennessean.
Technical Director Rod Reed told reporters that the accident that caused the injury occurred just before the break.
"He came close to the edge of the field and passed out", Reed said.
First responders and medical staff administered Abercrombie oxygen on the spot, before putting him in a stretcher and taking him away for further checks.
A Tennessee State executive told Chris Harris of WSMV in Nashville, Tennessee, that Abercrombie has undergone surgery at Vanderbilt University Medical Center.
Harris added that "we don't have any information yet on the type and extent of the damage" and that Tennessee State is trying to figure out when he was injured.
Abercrombie, sophomore, is in his first season with Tennessee State after transferring from Illinois.
He had made a total of five tackles before leaving the game, which brought his season total to 18 tackles.
Foreign buyers will be subject to higher stamp duty for purchasing property in the UK
Foreign buyers will be subject to higher stamp duty for purchasing property in the UK and the additional cash flow will be used to help the homeless, according to the new Labour plans.
The manoeuvre will neutralize the success of Corbyn's initiative to attract young voters
The stamp duty increase will be applied to taxpayers who do not pay taxes in the UK
The Treasury is planning to raise up to £120 million a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to higher stamp duty for purchasing property in the UK and the additional cash flow will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
The move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's initiative to attract young voters with the promise of more affordable housing and higher incomes.
The stamp duty increase will be applied to individuals and companies who do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional resources will support the Government's initiative to combat homelessness.
The surcharge, which is added to the current stamp duty, including the high levels introduced two years ago on second homes and buy-to-let properties, could be more than 3%.
The Treasury expects the move to raise up to £120 million a year.
An estimated 13% of new construction in London is purchased by non-residents, driving up prices and making it difficult for first-time home buyers to enter the housing market.
Many of the country's wealthier areas, especially in the capital, have become "ghost towns" because of the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the state.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a cut in the stamp tax to help younger people buy their first home.
He accused big construction companies of keeping property prices high by grabbing land without using it and encouraged Prime Minister May to give up quotas on affordable housing to fix Britain's 'housing disaster'.
Mr Corbyn has announced a number of striking proposals for housing reform, including rent controls and the elimination of wrongful evictions.
He also wants to give the council more powers over the construction of new buildings.
Prime Minister May said: "Last year I said I would be committed to re-establishing the British dream, which is that life should be better for the new generations.
And that means restoring the housing market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build a life here.
However, it would not be fair if buying a house was as easy for non-UK residents and for foreign companies as it is for resident UK workers.
For many people the dream of owning a home has become too distant and the dignity of the homeless remains a reality.
Jack Ross: "My greatest aspiration is to lead Scotland".
Sunderland's technical director Jack Ross says his "highest aspiration" is to eventually become Scotland manager.
The 42-year-old Scot is drawn to the challenge of re-electing the North-East side who are currently in third place in League One, three points from the top.
He arrived at the Stadium of Light this summer after being at the helm of St Mirren during last season's Scottish Premiership.
I wanted to play for my country as a footballer.
I've been in Series B and that's it", Ross told the BBC's Scottish programme Sportsound.
I grew up watching Scotland in Hampden with my dad as a kid and it's something I'll always remember.
However, this will only be possible if I succeed as a team manager.
Ross' predecessors at the helm of Sunderland were Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former coach of Alloa Athletic says he feels no anxiety about following such big names into an equally big team, having previously turned down offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
"Success for me right now is measured by the ability to get the team back into the Premier League".
"Considering the structure and facilities of the club, we can say that it belongs without a doubt to the Premier League", he said.
It's not an easy task, but I think I'll only succeed if I can get the team back on track.
Ross's managerial career began three years ago, after a spell as assistant manager at Dumbarton and 15 months as Hearts assistant manager.
He then helped Alloa to save themselves from relegation to the third tier and led St Mirren from the edge of relegation to the Championship title the following season.
Ross claims to feel much more at ease now than during his playing career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
This was probably a real turning point, he recalls about the direction of the Alloa.
I really thought the manager role was meant for me, more than the player.
It seems strange because I've worked well, I've earned a living and I've had some good results.
But playing can be tough.
There's a lot of stuff you have to deal with on a weekly basis.
I'm still dealing with it in terms of the stress and pressure of the job but the management seems good.
I've always wanted to direct, and now that I'm doing it, I feel much more at ease than I've ever felt in my life.
