According to one study, the best time to drink a pint is 5:30 p.m. on Saturday.
The summer heat wave has brought more income to struggling British pubs and more concern to catering services.
The data shows that pubs and bars saw sales increase by 2.7 percent in July, while restaurant revenues fell by 4.8 percent.
Peter Martin, of the business consultancy firm CGA, put the data together and commented: The persistence of the sun and England's long stay at the World Cups meant that July followed a similar path to June, when pubs were above 2.8 per cent, while restaurants were hit the hardest.
The drop of 1.8 per cent in catering in June worsened in July.
Pubs and bars where most people drink were the strongest, with a more uniform increase than the decline in restaurants.
The pubs where you eat have also suffered from the heat, though not to the extent of the restaurants.
It seems people just wanted to go out and have a drink.
In pubs and bars, beverage sales rose by 6.6 percent in the month, while food consumption fell by 3 percent.
Paul Newman, RSM's leisure and entertainment industry analyst, said: 'These results continue the trend we have seen since the end of April.
The weather and the impact of major social or sporting events remain the main factors when it comes to selling in the retail market.
Not surprisingly, restaurants continue to struggle, although a 4.8 percent annual decline in sales will be particularly severe in addition to continued cost pressures.
The long hot summer could not have come at a worse time for the restaurant industry and only time will tell whether the more moderate temperatures we enjoyed in August will give us the necessary respite.
Global pub and restaurant sales growth, including new openings, was 2.7 per cent in July, reflecting the decline in brand roll-outs.
The UK pub, bar and restaurant sales tracker Coffer Peach Tracker compiles and analyses performance data across 47 operating groups, with a combined turnover of over £9 billion, and is the industry benchmark.
