Nickel mining is also a major activity in the province, but is mostly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by several tsunamis in the last 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Another tsunami hit the western area of Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the seismic zone known as the Pacific Ring of Fire and is frequently hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the strongest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a massive earthquake on the west coast of Aceh province north of Sumatra caused a tsunami that hit 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, including more than half of Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra between late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on Nias Island off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude earthquake struck the southern part of Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that struck the southern coastline killing nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
The victims were over 1,100.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake struck one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, causing a 10-meter tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A slight earthquake hit Pidie Jaya Regency in Aceh causing destruction and panic among people who remembered the devastation of the 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
